  "prompt": "Is there any organic compound without carbon atom?",
  "response": "By definition, organic compounds primarily contain carbon atoms along with hydrogen and may also include other elements such as nitrogen, oxygen, sulfur, and phosphorus. Therefore, by traditional classification, a compound without carbon is not considered organic. \n\nHowever, there are compounds that may be referred to as \"organic\" in certain contexts, such as some organometallic compounds, but these still contain carbon. There are also compounds that are biologically significant but do not fit the classical definition of organic, such as water (H\u2082O), ammonia (NH\u2083), and others that might play roles in biological systems, but they are categorized as inorganic compounds. \n\nIn summary, there are no compounds classified as organic without carbon atoms.",
